            "text": ". However, in the first published case series, taste dysfunctions are always more frequent then olfactory disturbances, presenting alone in 10.2-22.5% of patients[2][3][4] . This finding could lead to the hypothesis that the correlation between the two dysfunctions is not so close and that there are other factors behind the gustatory disorders in these patients.AnosmiaACE2 is expressed on the nasal mucosa, where it participates in respiratory inflammatory diseases by regulating the levels of inflammatory peptides, such as bradykinin14 . However, in COVID-19 patients there does not seem to be present such an important inflammatory component and the alteration of the sense of smell is generally not accompanied by rhinitis symptoms 1,3 .Therefore, one hypothesis could be that the alterations are due to damage caused by the virus to the olfactory pathways. Anosmia has already been described in common coronavirus infections15,16 . In 2006, Hwang 17 described a case of anosmia that persisted for two years after SARS had been contracted. In 2001, Schwob et al.18 and Youngentob et al.19 evaluated the anatomopathological and functional consequences of olfactory bulb line variant mouse hepatitis virus intranasal inoculation in murine models. The histopathological analysis of the anosmic mice revealed a minimal destruction of the olfactory epithelium which was nonetheless abnormal due to the predominance of immature neurons, an indication of an accelerated cell turnover18,19 . The reduction in the neuronal lifespan in the epithelium is most likely to be the consequence of a decrease in the trophic support supplied by the bulb to the This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved. 5 sensory neurons, caused by the loss of mitral cells and the absence of dendrites of the surviving mitral and tufted cells from the glomerular layer",
